Part 1: Ridge

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer, make_column_selector
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.linear_model import Ridge, LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

ames_data = pd.read_csv("/Users/OwenBarberie/Desktop/GSB_544/AmesHousing.csv")

# filter
filtered_columns = ames_data.isna().sum() < 100
ames_cleaned = ames_data.loc[:, filtered_columns].dropna()

X = ames_cleaned.drop(columns=["SalePrice", "Order", "PID"])
y = ames_cleaned["SalePrice"]
# pipelines
transformer = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ("encode_cats", OneHotEncoder(sparse_output=False, handle_unknown='ignore'), make_column_selector(dtype_include=object)),
        ("scale_nums", StandardScaler(), make_column_selector(dtype_include=np.number))
    ],
    remainder="passthrough"
)

ridge_pipe = Pipeline([
    ("preprocessing", transformer),
    ("ridge", Ridge(alpha=1))
])

linear_pipe = Pipeline([
    ("preprocessing", transformer),
    ("linear", LinearRegression())
])
# cross validate
ridge_cv_scores = cross_val_score(ridge_pipe, X, y, cv=5, scoring="neg_root_mean_squared_error")
ridge_rmse_avg = -ridge_cv_scores.mean()
print(f"Cross-validated RMSE for Ridge Regression (alpha=1): {ridge_rmse_avg:.2f}")

linear_cv_scores = cross_val_score(linear_pipe, X, y, cv=5, scoring="neg_root_mean_squared_error")
linear_rmse_avg = -linear_cv_scores.mean()
print(f"Cross-validated RMSE for Ordinary Linear Regression: {linear_rmse_avg:.2f}")

# fitting both models
ridge_pipe.fit(X, y)
linear_pipe.fit(X, y)

# extract coefficients
ridge_coefs = ridge_pipe.named_steps["ridge"].coef_
linear_coefs = linear_pipe.named_steps["linear"].coef_

# feature names
preprocessed_data = transformer.fit_transform(X)
numeric_columns = make_column_selector(dtype_include=np.number)(X)
categorical_columns = make_column_selector(dtype_include=object)(X)
feature_names = transformer.named_transformers_["scale_nums"].get_feature_names_out(numeric_columns).tolist() + \
                transformer.named_transformers_["encode_cats"].get_feature_names_out(categorical_columns).tolist()
Cross-validated RMSE for Ridge Regression (alpha=1): 28871.92
Cross-validated RMSE for Ridge Regression (alpha=1): 28871.92
Cross-validated RMSE for Ordinary Linear Regression: 3597694085395859.00
Cross-validated RMSE for Ordinary Linear Regression: 3597694085395859.00
# plot
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
plt.plot(feature_names, ridge_coefs, 'o-', label="Ridge Coefficients (alpha=1)")
plt.plot(feature_names, linear_coefs, 'x-', label="Linear Regression Coefficients")
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.xlabel("Features")
plt.ylabel("Coefficient Values")
plt.title("Comparison of Ridge and Ordinary Linear Regression Coefficients")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Part 2: Ridge Tuning

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# param definition
param_grid = {
    "ridge__alpha": [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10]
}

# tune with gridsearch
ridge_tuner = GridSearchCV(ridge_pipe, param_grid, cv=5, scoring="neg_root_mean_squared_error", n_jobs=-1)
ridge_tuner.fit(X, y)

# find best
best_alpha = ridge_tuner.best_params_["ridge__alpha"]
best_rmse = -ridge_tuner.best_score_
print(f"Best alpha (lambda) for Ridge Regression: {best_alpha}")
print(f"Best cross-validated RMSE: {best_rmse:.2f}")
Best alpha (lambda) for Ridge Regression: 10
Best cross-validated RMSE: 28633.51

Part 3: Lasso

from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso

# lasso pipeline
lasso_pipe = Pipeline([
    ("preprocessing", transformer),
    ("lasso", Lasso(max_iter=10000))  # Increase max_iter to ensure convergence
])

# param grid
lasso_param_grid = {
    "lasso__alpha": [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10]
}

#tuning
lasso_tuner = GridSearchCV(lasso_pipe, lasso_param_grid, cv=5, scoring="neg_root_mean_squared_error", n_jobs=-1)
lasso_tuner.fit(X, y)

# best alpha value
best_lasso_alpha = lasso_tuner.best_params_["lasso__alpha"]
best_lasso_rmse = -lasso_tuner.best_score_
print(f"Best alpha (lambda) for Lasso: {best_lasso_alpha}")
print(f"Best cross-validated RMSE for Lasso: {best_lasso_rmse:.2f}")

# fit the best lasso model on the full dataset
best_lasso_model = lasso_tuner.best_estimator_
best_lasso_model.fit(X, y)
lasso_coefs = best_lasso_model.named_steps["lasso"].coef_

Part 4: Elestic Net

from sklearn.linear_model import ElasticNet

# elastic net pipeline
elastic_net_pipe = Pipeline([
    ("preprocessing", transformer),
    ("elastic_net", ElasticNet(max_iter=50000))
])

# tuning alpha (regularization) and l1_ratio (mixing parameter)
elastic_net_param_grid = {
    "elastic_net__alpha": [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10],   
    "elastic_net__l1_ratio": [0.1, 0.5, 0.9] 
}

# gridsearch to find best combo 
elastic_net_tuner = GridSearchCV(elastic_net_pipe, elastic_net_param_grid, cv=5, 
                                 scoring="neg_root_mean_squared_error", n_jobs=-1)
elastic_net_tuner.fit(X, y)

# best parameters
best_elastic_net_params = elastic_net_tuner.best_params_
best_elastic_net_rmse = -elastic_net_tuner.best_score_
print(f"Best parameters for Elastic Net: {best_elastic_net_params}")
print(f"Best cross-validated RMSE for Elastic Net: {best_elastic_net_rmse:.2f}")

# fitting elastic net on dataset 
best_elastic_net_model = elastic_net_tuner.best_estimator_
best_elastic_net_model.fit(X, y)
elastic_net_coefs = best_elastic_net_model.named_steps["elastic_net"].coef_

import pandas as pd
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, labs, theme, element_text, scale_y_continuous, scale_color_manual

# DataFrame for elastic net, ridge, and OLS
coefficients_df = pd.DataFrame({
    "Feature": feature_names,
    "ElasticNet": elastic_net_coefs,
    "Ridge": ridge_coefs,
    "OLS": linear_coefs
}).melt(id_vars="Feature", var_name="Model", value_name="Coefficient")

# filter out extremes for readability
coefficients_df = coefficients_df[coefficients_df['Coefficient'].between(-100000, 100000)]

# plot
(
    ggplot(coefficients_df, aes(x="Feature", y="Coefficient", color="Model")) +
    geom_point(position="jitter") +
    labs(
        title="Comparison of Elastic Net, Ridge, and OLS Coefficients",
        x="Features",
        y="Coefficient Value"
    ) +
    theme(
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=90, hjust=1, size=8),
        figure_size=(14, 6)
    ) +
    scale_y_continuous(limits=(-100000, 100000)) +  # Adjust y-axis limits as needed
    scale_color_manual(values=["#FF6347", "#4682B4", "#32CD32"])  # Customize colors for clarity
)
